Qualified professionals from the Luhya community should be allowed to freely work in the Rift Valley, a Western Kenya caucus has said.The Western Caucus for Change criticised the MPs and two governors from the Kalenjin community for opposing Prof Laban Ayiro&rsquo;s appointment as Moi University acting vice chancellor.&ldquo;This is not the first time we are being harassed, we witnessed Prof Teresa Akenga&rsquo;s appointment as VC of Eldoret University rejected,&rdquo; interim chairman Geoffrey Njuya told the Star on the phone on Sunday. He said professionals should be able to work anywhere in the country.